/*

Given a PostgreSQL table user_tags with the following schema:

user_id (integer) - Unique identifier for the user.
tags (string) - Comma-separated string of tags associated with the user.
You are tasked to write a PostgreSQL query that selects all unique tags, counts the number of occurrences for each tag (tag_count), and assigns a rank to each tag based on the number of occurrences (tag_rank). The tags with the highest number of occurrences should have the lowest rank. If two or more tags have the same number of occurrences, they should be ranked in alphabetical order. In other words, among tags that have the same tag_count value, the one that comes first in alphabetical order will receive the lower rank (higher position).

For example, consider the following sample data:

user_id | tags
--------+------------
1       | word1,word2,word3
2       | word2,word4
3       | word3,word5,word6,word7
The desired output for this sample data is:

tag_rank | tag   | tag_count
---------+-------+---------
1        | word2 | 2
2        | word3 | 2
3        | word1 | 1
4        | word4 | 1
5        | word5 | 1
6        | word6 | 1
7        | word7 | 1
GLHF!



*/



SELECT ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC, tag) AS tag_rank,
       tag,
       COUNT(*) AS tag_count
FROM (SELECT 
             unnest(string_to_array(tags, ',')) AS tag
      FROM user_tags
) t
GROUP BY tag;


